│ correctly detecting broken dominance created by the pass. Fixing the          │
│ insertion point selection should prevent the verifier from tripping.          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By ensuring shuffles are emitted at insertion points that are after their     │
│ operand(s) definitions, we avoid violating dominance. The proposed changes    │
│ wrap shuffle creation with an InsertPointGuard and set the builder’s          │
│ insertion point after the relevant defining instruction(s). This should fix   │
│ the crash for the provided reproducer and similar cases where the current     │
│ builder insertion point did not account for operand dominance. If further     │
│ issues arise with cross-block operands, a more advanced solution could        │
│ compute a nearest common dominator and place the shuffle at the first non-PHI │
│ in that block, but the proposed conservative approach should cover the common │
